Secrets, and why environment variables aren't secret.

Every tutorial does this, and it's wrong for real credentials: running with dash e, database-password equals hunter-two. Convenient, but not secret. That password leaks in at least four places. First, docker inspect prints the whole environment block, so anyone with daemon access reads it. Second, the process environment, under slash proc, exposes it on the host to anyone who can read it. Third, the shell history on the machine that launched it. And fourth, crash dumps and logs, that helpfully capture the environment at crash time. On top of that, environment variables are inherited by every child process, so every shell-out inside the container sees the password too. Environment variables are for configuration, like a log level, or feature flags, not for secrets.

The container-native way is a secret file, mounted at a known path, readable only by the app's user. In Compose, you give the service a secrets list, and declare the secret at the top level, pointing at a file. Compose mounts the file at slash run slash secrets slash the secret name, with restrictive permissions, and the app reads the path, not an environment variable.

Notice the common convention: you pass database-password-file, a path, rather than database-password, a value. Many official images support that file suffix natively. The same secrets syntax scales up to Swarm secrets, in module nine, which are encrypted at rest and in transit across the cluster, and to build-kit secret mounts, which keep secrets out of image layers at build time, back in module two. The rule: secrets are files, with tight permissions, never environment variables.
